Interactive SHAP Plot of Model Decision-making¶

  • Extreme gradient boosting decision-making explored on the curated training data.

  • Training data genes are given a score between 0 to 1 which the machine learning model is trying to predict - identifying most likely causal blood pressure genes.

seed = 0


#load data and identify training scores:
dataset = pd.read_csv("BP_training.txt", header=0, sep="\t")
data = dataset[["Gene", "BPlabel"]]
data["BPlabel_encoded"] = data["BPlabel"].map(
    {"most likely": 1, "probable": 0.75, "least likely": 0.1}
)
Y = data["BPlabel_encoded"]
data = data.drop(["BPlabel"], 1)

#load data as selected features:
X_boruta_sel = pd.read_csv("selected_features_training_data.csv", header=0)
X_boruta_sel.columns = [
    regex.sub("_", col) if any(x in str(col) for x in set(("[", "]", "<"))) else col
    for col in X_boruta_sel.columns.values
]
#train:test split:
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(
    X_boruta_sel, Y, test_size=0.2, random_state=0
)
#build model:
cb = CatBoostRegressor(depth=3, iterations=50, learning_rate=0.14114919579534718, random_seed=seed, verbose=False)

cb.fit(X_train, Y_train)
df3 = pd.DataFrame(data=X_boruta_sel, columns=X_boruta_sel.columns)
df3.columns = [
    regex.sub("_", col) if any(x in str(col) for x in set(("[", "]", "<"))) else col
    for col in X_boruta_sel.columns.values
]
X_importance = X_test
explainer = shap.TreeExplainer(cb)
shap_values = explainer.shap_values(X_importance)

#code toggle: 
javascript_functions = {False: "hide()", True: "show()"}
button_descriptions  = {False: "Show code", True: "Hide code"}


def toggle_code(state):

    """
    Toggles the JavaScript show()/hide() function on the div.input element.
    """

    output_string = "<script>$(\"div.input\").{}</script>"
    output_args   = (javascript_functions[state],)
    output        = output_string.format(*output_args)

    display(HTML(output))


def button_action(value):

    """
    Calls the toggle_code function and updates the button description.
    """

    state = value.new

    toggle_code(state)

    value.owner.description = button_descriptions[state]


state = False
toggle_code(state)

button = widgets.ToggleButton(state, description = button_descriptions[state])
button.observe(button_action, "value")

display(button)

SHAP Heatmap:¶

  • SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) is a game theoretic approach to explain the output of any machine learning model [1].
  • SHAP values indicate the degree to which a feature affected the model's output prediction for each sample.
  • Positive SHAP values (red) indicate a positive increase in the output score, and vice versa for negative SHAP values (blue) and lower model scores.
  • The f(x) plot shows final model prediction value.
  • The y-axis indicates order of feature importance (descending importance with ExomiserScore as the most important feature).
In [2]:
shap.initjs()
explainer = shap.TreeExplainer(cb)
shap_values = explainer(X_boruta_sel)
shap.plots.heatmap(shap_values, max_display=8)

SHAP Force Plot:¶

  • Interactive plot of model scores, with the x-axis being the rows of genes and the y-axis being the output model prediction for that gene.
  • Both x-axis and y-axis measures can be altered for different visualizations.
  • Clicking within the plot provides row number along the x-axis, for which the gene symbol can be viewed within the raw training data file.

Interactive Table¶

  • Clicking within the interactive force plot provides row numbers (index_num) that can be searched for to identify gene symbols in the raw training data (sample of rows shown below).
  • The table includes: index number, gene symbols, gene significance in ingenuity pathway analysis (IPA), predicted model score, training score, the features used by the model (before feature imputation), and the cluster ordering that matches the heatmap and forceplot instances order.
  • Rows are in the same order a the x-axis of the heatmap and force plot.

    return X_interactive[X_interactive['Gene']==x]
